# üêû bug report

### Affected Package

The issue is caused by package @angular/cli (or @angular/router)

### Is this a regression?

Not sure

### Description

If a component declared by a lazy loaded module is referenced, but not used, by `app.module.ts`, it will be included in `main.js` instead of in a lazy loaded chunk.

```ts
// all-routes.ts
export const NORMAL_ROUTE: Route = {
  component: NormalCompComponent,
  path: '',
  pathMatch: 'full',
};

export const LAZY_MODULE_ROUTE: Route = {
  path: 'lazy',
  loadChildren: () => import('./lazy/lazy.module').then((m) => m.LazyModule),
};

export const LAZY_ROUTE: Route = {
  path: '',
  component: LazyCompComponent
};
```

```ts
// app.module.ts
...
  declarations: [
    AppComponent,
    NormalCompComponent,
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule,
    AppRoutingModule
  ],
...
```

```ts
// app-routing.module.ts
...
import { NORMAL_ROUTE, LAZY_MODULE_ROUTE } from './all-routes';

const routes: Routes = [NORMAL_ROUTE, LAZY_MODULE_ROUTE];
...
```

```ts
// lazy.module.ts
...
  declarations: [
    LazyCompComponent
  ],
  imports: [
    CommonModule,
    LazyRoutingModule
  ]
...
```

```ts
// lazy-routing.module.ts
...
import { LAZY_ROUTE } from './all-routes';

const routes: Routes = [LAZY_ROUTE];
...
```

This configuration makes `lazy-module-chunk.js` practically empty (~500B), as `LazyCompComponent` is imported in `main.js`.

Now move this statement from `all-routes.ts` to `lazy-routing.module.ts` (and remove import):
```ts
export const LAZY_ROUTE: Route = {
  path: '',
  component: LazyCompComponent
};
```

And then the component is included in the lazy loaded chunk, as it should be.

Is this expected behavior? I'm not sure why this happens. I had assumed Angular statically analyzed the imported components somehow, but apparently this does not happen, and an unused import somewhere down the import tree moves the component to the root module.

